descript.abstract: The San Diego Regional Enterprise Zone was adopted October 15,2006. It includes portions of San Diego in the Second,Third,Fourth, Seventh and Eighth Council Districts, as well as parts of the City of Chula Vista and National City.
descript.purpose: An Enterprise Zone is an economically disadvantaged area in which businesses can receive substantial state tax credits and other competitive advantages. Enterprise Zones are geographically defined and created by the state of California to encourage business investments in areas where they are traditionally low and to spur job growth in areas of high unemployment.

idinfo.accconst: Businesses within the Enterprise Zone are eligible for tax credits on their California Business income tax.
idinfo.useconst: Tax credits are more beneficial than tax deductions. If the tax credits exceed the amount of taxes owed for that year, unused tax credits can be carried forward to future tax years.
